Definition: Competencies that enable people to live, work, and innovate in ways that support sustainability and reduce ecological harm.
Purpose: Help transition economies toward low‑carbon, resource‑efficient systems.
Examples: Renewable energy design, waste reduction, sustainable agriculture, eco‑friendly construction, and environmental monitoring.

Global Demand: As industries “green” their processes, workers need new skills to stay relevant.
Education Priority: UNICEF emphasizes integrating green skills into school curricula to prepare youth for climate‑resilient careers.
Economic Transition: UNIDO highlights that by 2030, industries must retrofit for sustainability, creating new occupations and reshaping existing ones.

Engineering & Technical Skills: Designing renewable energy systems, eco‑buildings.
Science Skills: Physics, biology, and chemistry applied to sustainability.
Operations Management: Life‑cycle management, lean production, sustainable supply chains.
Monitoring Skills: Environmental audits, compliance with green regulations.

Green skills are essential for future careers and everyday life, equipping people to adapt to climate change, innovate sustainably, and build a fairer, greener economy.
